<para id="para-00006">In contrast with water, methanol, and ammonia, molecules such as carbon dioxide, methane, ethane, and benzene have zero dipole moments. Because of the symmetrical structures of these molecules, the individual bond polarities and lone-pair contributions exactly cancel.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
<media alt="An illustration shows 4 images. The first image shows the kekulé line bond structure of carbon dioxide with a carbon atom double bonded to two oxygen atoms on its sides. The second image shows the kekulé line bond structure of methane with a central carbon atom having a dash bonded and wedge bonded hydrogen atoms and also line bonded with 2 hydrogen atoms. The third image shows the kekulé line bond structure of ethane with 2 carbon atoms with a single bond between them and a line bonded dash bonded and wedge bonded hydrogen atoms for each. The fourth image shows the kekulé line bond structure of benzene with hexagonal carbon ring with each of these carbon atoms line bonded to a hydrogen atom.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_02_02_003.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<example id="exam-00001">
<title>Predicting the Direction of a Dipole Moment</title>
<para id="para-00007">Make a three-dimensional drawing of methylamine, CH<sub>3</sub>NH<sub>2</sub>, and show the direction of its dipole moment (<m:math><m:mi>µ</m:mi></m:math> = 1.31).</para>
<para id="para-00008"><title><span class="red-text">Strategy</span></title>Look for any lone-pair electrons, and identify any atom with an electronegativity substantially different from that of carbon. (Usually, this means O, N, F, Cl, or Br.) Electron density will be displaced in the general direction of the electronegative atoms and the lone pairs.</para>
<para id="para-00009"><title><span class="cyan-text">Solution</span></title>Methylamine contains an electronegative nitrogen atom with a lone pair of electrons. The dipole moment thus points generally from –CH<sub>3</sub> toward the lone pair.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00004">
<media alt="An illustration of methylamine (μ = 1.31) shows a blue lobe with a pair of electrons. The kekulé line bond structure shows a carbon atom having a line bonded, dash bonded, and wedge bonded each to a hydrogen atom. The carbon shares a single bond with a nitrogen atom which is dash bonded and wedge bonded each to a hydrogen atom."><image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_02_02_004.jpg"/></media>
</figure>
</example>
